77-81 Vesey Street, at the S.E. corner of Washington Street, showing only the lower stories of building concerned. Shown on the extreme right is a portion of the Washington Market, reputed to be the largest wholesale
vegetable and fruit market in the world.

August 1, 1930.

P. L. Sperr.

(1) A general view, east from the New York Telephone Building, 140 West Street, from Vesey to Barclay Streets, showing in the background the East River, with the Brooklyn Bridge; at the left, is the Municipal Building, (at Centre and Chambers Streets); and in the centre, the Woolworth Building, (233 Broadway, between Barclay Street and Park Place).

P. L. Sperr.

(2) The same, from a different angle.

P. L. Sperr.

(3) The same, another view.

P. L. Sperr.

(1) Vesey Street, north side, east from, but not including Washington Street. The view shows the new Post Office in process of construction. Towering over all is the Woolworth Building.

August 31, 1935.

P. L. Sperr.

(2) The same; another view. August 31, 1935.

P. L. Sperr.

(3) The same, at an earlier date, showing clearance; on the site where steel construction is in progress on the United States Post Office Building. The building to the right of the Woolworth, is the 44-story Transportation Building at the S.W. corner of Barclay Street and Broadway.

April 3, 1934.

P. L. Sperr.
